<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-699-820  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 699 820.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  August 1989 v29 n8 p42(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What should instructional designers know about general systemstheory?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Salisbury, David F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Instructional systems design (ISD) is closely related to generalsystems theory (GST).andP;  GST consists of four broad categories ofconcepts: systematic and descriptive factors, factors dealing withthe regulation and maintenance of systems, factors dealing withdynamics and change within a system, and factors dealing withdecline and breakdown of systems.andP;  Instructional designers shouldrealize that ISD is the application of GST to the field ofeducation, and should develop a working knowledge of GST terms,concepts, and applications.andP;  The most promising approaches tointroducing GST concepts into ISD programs are to interspersegeneral systems concepts throughout ISD course offerings, and toinclude general systems concepts in ISD courses at the macrolevel.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Systems TheoryInstructional DesignAnalytical Techniques.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Four categories of GST concepts as described by Young (1964).andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>